Vheadline
p2
VCelebrating a maestro
p3
sVnews
p4
VThe 10-day annual Chembai Music Festival, held in commemoration with the 112th birth anniversary celebrations of maestro Chembai Vaidyanatha Bhagavathar,  featured concerts by veteran artistes as well as young talents.Crowd-puller Sanjay Subramaniam started off his vocal concert with a varnam in Sahana, followed  by &#8216;Vande mataram&#8217; in Kedaram.He chose Begada for the main piece of the evening. The kriti &#8216;Nadopasana&#8217; in praise of Siva, set to Adi tala,  saw him  revelling in manodharma sangitam and the nuances of the raga were delineated with finesse. The thaniavarthanam was performed by Thanjavoor Ramadas on the mridangam and Trippunnithura Radhakrishnan on the ghatam. Avaneeswaram S.R.Vinu accompanied on the violin.S. Mahathi,  a disciple of T.N. Seshagopalan,  mellifluously rendered &#8216;O Rangasayi&#8217; in Kamboji.  The kriti, which was set to Adi tala, was the high point of her vocal concert. In the virutham, she eulogised the deity of Srirangam temple.S.R. Rajeswari provided  support on the violin, while  Kottayam Santhosh on the mridangam and Anchal Krishna Iyer on the ghatam presented the thaniavartanam.  Mahathi&#8217;s repertoire of kritis included rich pieces such as  &#8216;Sakthi Ganapathim&#8217; (Natta),  &#8216;Kripa nidhe,&#8217; a rare composition in Hamsanandi using dhaivatha prayoga, &#8216;Samajavaragamana&#8217; (Hindolam), &#8216;Narajanma bandhaka&#8217; (Madhuvanti), &#8216;Ramachandra prabhu&#8217; (Sindubhairavi) and a tillana of Muthiah Bhagavathar.Vocalist Vijayalekshmi Subramaniam&#8217;s  concert was noted for  her exceptional gamaka prayogas.  She began her concert with Tyagaraja&#8217;s &#8216;Brova barama&#8217; in Bahudari, followed by &#8216;Dharani telisi,&#8217; another Tyagaraja kriti  in Sudhasaveri. A rare composition &#8216;Sree Swaminatha namasthe&#8217; of Muthuswamy Dikshitar in Khamaj was received with applause.   Easwara Varma accompanied her on the violin.The  interactions between Vijayalekshmi and the mridangam artiste  Cherthalai R. Jayadevan were well-appreciated.  Ghatam was played by Perukavu S.L. Sudheer in the thani. She concluded her recital with a few thukkadas.Cherthalai K.N.Ranganatha Sharma , son of  Cherthalai Narayana Iyer, gave an  erudite performance. Adhering to classicism and in a robust voice, he commenced his concert with a Thodi varnam.Dikshitar&#8217;s &#8216;Vallabhanayaka&#8217; in Begada was followed by &#8216;Mari vera&#8217; of Syama Sastri  in Anandabhairavi. &#8216;Nammi vachana,&#8217; a Kovoor pancharatna kriti of Tyagaraja and &#8216;Pattividaratho&#8217; in Manjari were noted for their lyrical beauty. The main attraction was the Kambhoji kriti &#8216;O Rangasayi,&#8217; composed by Tyagaraja and  set to Adi tala. The ragabhava was sketched perfectly by T.H Subramaniam on the violin. The thaniavarthanam saw smooth exchanges between Trivandrum Balaji on the mridangam and Manjoor Unnikrishnan on the ghatam.The vocal recital of Krishnakumar Varma,  a disciple of D.K. Jayaraman and D.K. Pattammal,  was accompanied by Kadannad V.R. Haridas on the violin. Krishnakumar opened his concert with a Begada varnam, and moved on to render &#8216;Sree Maha Ganapathim&#8217; in Atana. The rendition of &#8216;Enthuku peddala&#8217; in Sankarabharanam stood out for excellence in raga alapana. The thaniavartanam was played by Trivandrum Raveendran and Ennakad Maheswaran on the mridangam and the ghatam respectively.Two instrumental concerts by Trivandrum B. Sivakumar and Mudikondan S.N.Ramesh on the harmonium and the veena respectively, charmed audiences.  Sivakumar, a disciple of Kudamaloor Janardanan, gave an exceptional recital of Swati Tirunal&#8217;s &#8216;Santhatham tavaka&#8217; in Kharaharapriya set to Adi tala.The taniavarthanam was performed by Maheshmani on the tabla and Trivandrum Kishore on the mridangam.  &#8216;Theerathu vilayattu pillai&#8217; was interspersed with a ragamalika comprising Sindhubhairavi, Khamaj, Shanmughapriya and Mand.Ramesh who follows the gayaki style in veena  started his concert with a Bhairavi varnam. &#8216;Vatapi Ganapathim bhajeham&#8217; in Hamsadwani and &#8216;Nada thanumani&#8217; in Chitharanjini revealed his expertise in manodharma sangitam. The popular &#8216;Moksha mogala dha&#8217; in Saramati was marked by chaste swara sancharam and apt gamaka prayogas.Mavelikara R.V.Rajesh and Trivandrum Karthikeyan performed the thaniavarthanam.Short concerts were presented by Arjun Krishna, S.Sudheesh, S.Balasubramaniam, Sarada Kalyanasundaram and Mahadevan.The festival was organised by the Sri Chembai Memorial Trust, Thiruvananthapuram.
